TY  - JOUR
AU  - Piketty, Thomas
AU  - Saez, Emmanuel
T1  - Income Inequality in the United States, 1913–1998*
PY  - 2003
Y1  - 2003/02/01
DO  - 10.1162/00335530360535135
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 118
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 41
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper presents new homogeneous series on top shares of income and wages from 1913 to 1998 in the United States using individual tax returns data. Top income and wages shares display a U-shaped pattern over the century. Our series suggest that the large shocks that capital owners experienced during the Great Depression and World War II have had a permanent effect on top capital incomes. We argue that steep progressive income and estate taxation may have prevented large fortunes from fully recovering from these shocks. Top wage shares were flat before World War II, dropped precipitously during the war, and did not start to recover before the late 1960s but are now higher than before World War II. As a result, the working rich have replaced the rentiers at the top of the income distribution.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/00335530360535135
ER  - 



